    "Then ⃗ ∂v = {e 1, e 2, e3, e 4 } where e 1, e 2, e 3, e 4 are the four oriented edges pointing into v. Given a boundary labelling l: ⃗ ∂v → Irr C we let H v (l) ⊂ H v be the subspace of H v corresponding to the direct summand C(l(e 1) ⊗ l(e 2) → l(e 3) ⊗ l(e 4)).",
    "ThenH v = l∈L ∂ (v) H v (l).Given a finite region C we writeH C:= H V C = l∈L(C) H C (l), where H C (l):= v∈V C H v (l| ⃗ ∂v).The string-net subspace associated to C isH C 1:= l∈L SN (C) H C (l) =   e∈E C A e   H C,i.e.",
    "the string-net constraints are imposed along all edges of C. As the notation reflects, the string-net subspace of C depends only on the 1-skeleton C 1.We further decompose the string-net subspace according to boundary labellings.For b ∈ L ∂ (C) we denote by L b (C) the set of labellings l of C such that l| ⃗ ∂C = b.",
    "Similarly, L b SN (C) is the set of string-net labellings l of C such that l| ⃗ ∂C = b.Then we haveH C 1 = b∈L ∂ (C) H b C 1 with H b C 1:= l∈L b SN (C) H C (l).",
